{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_gaston_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583978/1910121101/0698.xml":{"full_text":"___u_njmn,iMUu ji.it Him...i jii n rum nr____\nThe Great Christmas Store\nThis big store is now one mass of\nholiday gift goods including toys, fancy\nchina, cut glass and hundreds of thou\nsands of other useful things for gifts.\nSpecial Prices made to merchants and Sunday Schools\nAll Sorts ot New Christ\nmas Gitts Are Here tor Yon\nSilverware and other\nChrlKlmaa gifts.\nSliver Chafing\nDlahea, Percolator*,\nSliver Serving\nDlahea, Cut Glass,\nFancy Clocks, Silver\nTea Sela, Sliver Syrup Pllchera, Sliver Pilch\ners, Silver Salad Dishes, Sliver Gravy, Soup\nor Punch I.adles, In Cases, Orange Spoons,\nTeaspoons In Cases and thousands of other\npretty silver things that will make good\n1 gifts. All at reduced prices.\nTOYS\n10c size Jack-in-tlie-Box at 3c\n10c size Jumping Jacks at 3o\n10c size Tin Horns at.3c\nLarge Jumping Jacks.5c\n10c size Toy Hatchets .5c\n10c size Toy Irons at.5c\n10c size Bisque Babies at .5c\nWheelbarrows at ..23c to 98c\n10c Painted House at.5c\n25c good size Drums.10c\n25c Wood Guns at.10c\n25g ABC Books at.10c\n50c size Tool Chests.23c\n50c size Autos and Clowns\nat.23c\nThousands of Mechanical Toys\nat .23c to $10\nunmi* up yrt.im\n$35 Haviland Dinner\nSet $24.95\n100-plece Haviland China\nDinner Sets. Several beau\ntiful new decorations and\nshapes to choose from, and\nevery piece In the set the\nmost useful. These sets\nsell regularly for J35.00,\nand are considered cheap\nat that price.\nNow Specially Priced\nAt $24.95\nTHOUSANDS AND MILLIONS OF DOLLS\nBaby Dolls, Kid Dolls, Bisque Dolls, Un\nbreakable Dolls, China Dolls, Indian Dolls, Jap\nanese Dolls, Negro Dolls and Dolls from all over\nthe world and all selling at reduced prices.\n25c Pretty Dressed Dolls, in boxes, at_9c\n50c Pretty Dressed Dolls, in boxes, at_23c\n$1.50 Kid Dolls, With Bisque Head, at_95c\nDull lied* 10c to *1.50\nMarion Harland Coffee Pots\u2014Nickle Plated\n1-piut Marion Harland Coffee Pots.98c\n1-quart Marion Harland Coffee Pots_$1.23\nTHE FAIR Phones 2-quart Marion Harland Coffee Pots.$1.55\n2020 2nd Ave. 88 3-quart Marion Harland Coffee Pots.$1.70\n2021 3rd Ave. 188 4-quart Marion Harland Coffee Pots.$1.85\nTHE PARIS APACHE\nJNJEAL LIFE\nQuite Unlike Theatrical Person\nOne Expects to See\nr\nCRIMINALS FOR GLORY\n\nIn RulHr the Young Ruffian In a\nMember of the Working tinea\n4 R ho Will Not\nfrom the New York Evening POBt.\nParis\u2014The Paris \"apache\" is becoming\nknown the world over. If you believe\ncertain newspapers, we of Paris are lia\nble to be murdered every time we walk\nout In the street by night. American\ntourists are beginning to ask us to show\nthem an apache, as if the great city had\nthem on tap for its sightseers. The\napache is not quite so easy.\nApache is a noun masculine and applied\nto males. Paris women are not apaches,\neven when they wear a knife under their\nstocking or that more modern and dan\ngerous weapon\u2014a hatpin\u2014in their hair,\ni The apaches are young also, from 15 to\n*0; you seldom hear of one older. The\nmajority of those who get Into the news\npapers *re on the turn to 20. And, what\never may be said of their morals\u2014extant,\nthough peculiar\u2014they are not profession\nals of the white slave trade. These are\nquite too well dressed and well paid to\nbe confounded with apaches living from\nband to month. Also, the apache Is not\ng plokpocket, though he may go In for\nan honorable' bit of burglary or violent\nrobbery when occasion offers,\ni In fact, a Paris apache is little else\nthan a youthful Parisian of the working\nclasses who has made up his mind not\nto work.\nA Frenchman might as reasonably ask\nto be shown a mlllloaive In New York as\n\u00abn American expect to have an apache\nIdentified for him In Paris. The cap tilt\ned back to show the love-locks\u2014\"roufla\nquettes\u201d\u2014plastered down on the fore\nbead, the short jacket and wide-footed\ntiousers, and the dangling cigarette held\nbetween lower lip and gum may be used\nfor theatrical purposes. In art history\nthey belong to the \"Alphonse\u201d or low\nclass woman's bully\u2014and long preceucu\nthe apache age.\nThe real apache, those who are giving\nthe Paris police so much trouble, avoid\ntheatricals and try to dress und look\nas much as possible like well behaved\nyoung workmen. Their clothes and man\nners may suffer from their determina\ntion to live without work, but they are\ntoo afraid of the police not to pretend\nto have worked once, and to be looking\n\u25a0till for work. Many even work intermit\ntently, when they have no other way to\nrul*e the wind, or because they are only\nhalf-hearted apaches.\nBand Together In Gangs\nAs Is natural to the unripe age of\napaches, and tohthe sociable instincts of\nyouth, they band together In gangs.\nSometimes It Is neighborhood, sometimes\na leader who under better conditions\nmight have become a Napoleon or a\nRoosevelt, that unites the gang and holds\n/It together. Naturally each gang fights\nwith rival gangs. Naturally each gang\nas Its \u201cgirls\u201d and wages heroic battles\nRheumatism Epidemic.\nPrescription by Prominent Doctor\nClaimed Positive Core\nThose who have tried this say It has\nno equal for quickly curing chronic\nand acute rheumatism and baclc-ache.\n\"Get one ounce of syyup of Sarsaparilla\ncompound and one ounce of Torts com\npound. Then get half a pint of good\nwhiskey (or sherry wine if It is pre\nferred) and put the other two ingredi\nents Into It. Take a tablespoonful of\nthis mixture before each meal and at\nbed time. Shake the bottle before\nusing.\" The good effects ate felt the\nftr\u00bbt day. Any druggist lias these in\ngredients on hand or will quickly get\nthem from his wholesale house.\nabout them. Naturally also in their lit\ntle world of the Paris slums, each apache\ni3 likely to look to his girl for the money\nhe needs. As she may fail him and his\nown settled determination not to work\ndoes not bring him money, he is further\nmore likely to resort to any violence nec\nessary to procure it, sometimes as a sol\nitary footpad, oftener as a bandit infest\ning dark street corners with his gang.\nAnd this is why he is so often confound\ned with the mere white slaver and thief.\nMany of his worst pranks, murder In\ncluded are not for money at all, but for\nglory or to avenge his honor in his own\nworld.\nWhat is the problem In all this? Evi\ndently the Paris apache is not essentially\ndifferent from the wrell-nigh extinct Lon\ndon -\u201chooffgrah\" or San Francisco \u201chood\nlum.\u201d A sociologist would begin by in\nvestigating the origin and evolution of\nthe breed.\nA Problem for Parim\nIt must always have existed in Paris\nin the latent state. If it has suddenly\ncome to light\u2014chiefly the uncertain light\ncf night lamps propitious to dark deeds\u2014\nthere must be a reason for it. Whatever\nthe reason may be\u2014parents\u2019 carelessness\nor loss of authority, lack of formation\nof conscience since religion has disap\npeared. decay of serious apprenticeship\nto trades, freedom of alcohol and debauch\nfrom extreme youth\u2014there is no present\nquestion of suppressing the' breed in It.4l\norigin.\nOnly repressive measures remain. Pre\nfect of Police Lepine, on whom the bur\nden is cast, says openly that penal laws\nalready existing would do much if en\nforced; and he blames the leniency of\nthe police courts. Here is an example:\nOn 26 out of the 31 days of last July,\npersons in Paris w\u2019ere shot with revolv\nersers. Of these 56 crimes 18 were due\nto apaches pure and simple. If the laws\nconcerning the carrying of concealed\nweapons were enforced, tills would not\nhave been possible. Can such laws be\nenforced?\nAll this has led to an agitation which\nis to come up in parliament. Why not\nuse the successful London remedy, the\ncat-o\u2019-nine-tails? First, say all republi\ncans, because it is contrary to the human\nprinciples of the French Revolution. Sec\nond, says nearly everyone, because polit\nical influence would intervene to save\napaches of the right party\u2014and to dis\ngrace by a w\u2019hipplng those of the oppo\nsite party, apaches or not.\n\u2019Phone Girls to Go\nFrom the Kansas City Star.\nIt is only a matter of time when the\nday of the \u201chello girl\u201d will end, accord\nin*; to O. C. Snider, general manager of\nthe Kansas City Home Telephone com\npany. Mr. Snider has returned from a\ntrip taken with a committee of the Home\ncompany stockholders to see automatic\ntelephone* connections.\n\u201cWe found nothing that could be de\npended on, although several plants were\nvisited,\u201d Mr. Snider said today. \u201cMany\nbij; plants are equipped y/ith automatic\nconnectors, but no satisfactory test has\nbeen made yet. The inventions along\nthat line are getting closer to perfec\ntion and it won\u2019t be many years until\ngirl operators will not be needed. The\nstockholders of the company are eager\nto gtv\u2019e the quickest possible service and\nto avoid mistakes. Mistakes will be\nmade so long as human beings work\nas operator*.\"*\nOne of the largest cities which has\nautomatic telephone connectors is Oma\nha. The system has not been used long\nenough to show w-hether fewer mistakes\nare made by the machinery than by the\naverage \u201chello girl,\u201d Mr. Snyder said\nMore than one thousand telephone oper\nators are employed b ythe two companies\nin Kansas City. The use of mechanical\noperators would cheapen operating ex\npenses.\nA Strange Situation\n\u2019From Harper\u2019s Weekly.\n\u201cHumor is a funny thing,\u201d said Binks.\n\u201cIt ought to be,\u201d said the Philosopher.\n\u201cOh, I don\u2019t mean that way,\u201d said\nBinks. \u201cI mean that It is a strange\nthing. Now', I can\u2019t speak French, but\nrI can always understand a French joke,\nand I can speak English, but I\u2019m blest\nif I can see an English joke.\u201d\n\u201cMost people are,\u201d said the Philoso\npher.\n\u201cAre what?\u201d said Binks.\n\u201cBlest if they can see an English joke,\u201d\nsaid the Philosopher. \u201cIt is a sign of an\nunusually keen vision.\u201d\nSurely Must Be\nFrom the Baltimore American.\n\u201cWhat kind of people are your new\nneighbors?\u201d\n\u201cI don\u2019t know much about them, but\nthey must be awful good-natured.\nThey\u2019ve had the same cook for almost\ntwo weeks.\u201d\nVACATION FOR\nJHE ANIMALS\nFrom the Christian Science Monitor.\nPine Ridge Farm Is the country an-1\nnex of the Animal Rescue League of\nBoston, and Is situated inrDedham, near\nthe dividing line between that town and\nNeedham. The visitor reaches it by car\nriage from JDedliam, or by a short walk\nfrom the Needham cars, which pass\nFine Street.\nLeaving the station at Dedham, we\npass several fine public buildings and\ncross the bridge near the boat clubhouse\nwiiere a picturesque view of the river\nand meadows spreads out on either side.\nThrough a clump of trees we catch a\nglimpse of historic Powder Rock, one I\nof the landmarks of the town, where\narms were stored during the Revolution\nary war. Then a shady, winding coun\ntry road leads to Pine Ridge.\nFrom the high fence of wire which\nsurrounds the premises, it is apparent\nthat it is not an ordinary farm, but the\nsunny orchard and the cottages beyond\nlook homelike and attractive. The cot\ntage is shaded by a number of tall pines\nwhere the wind whispers all day long\nin summer, and an atmosphere of peace\nsurrounds the entire place.\nIn a weird inclosure, where sweet peas\nwere growing over the outside, were a\nnumber of Angora eats, tlie special pets\nof the caretaker, and in an adjoining\ninclosure were two or three pigeons,\nwhile In a cage hanging from the top\nwas a young hawk which has had a\nsomewhat unusual career for a bird of\nhis age. \u201cPeter' 'fell from the nest when\nvery young, was picked up in the Fen\nway in Boston and carried to the league\nhome on Carver street, and from there\nwas sent to Pine Ridge. He is very\ntame and has proved so interesting that\nhe has won the affection of the family,\nand although be is not considered a\nsafe citizen to be allowed in the woods\nhe has had considerable freedom and\nflies around the inclosure with the pig\neons.\nHaven of Rent for Horses\nFollowing a board walk which wound\nup the hill we came to the stable. Here\nart? a number of horses, two or three\npensioners, other city work horses,\nspending a brief vacation, and some\ndisabled horses receiving special care.\nTht; stable is clean and dry, the stalls\nroomy and each has a wlndowr overlook\ning the surrounding grove of oak trees.\nThe horses were gazing out of these\nwindows, with the most evident enjoy\nment, and surely It must be a welcome\nrelief to these hard-working city horses\nto find such a haven of rest. The pad\ndocks run down the hill to the west,\nand It is said that one livery stable\nhorse brought here, when let out into\na paddock, was so delighted with the\nfreedom that she rolled and ran and\ngalloped for about half an hour wlthoitt\nstopping. Some interesting stories are\ntold of these vacationers and some very\npathetic ones. Robin put his head out\nof his stall and asked for a lump of\nsugar. A hag of carrots and one of\nsugar soon disappeared, as each horse\nwithin reach had to have a little treat.\nFlowers growing here and there add\nbrightness to the place and through the\ntrees there are occasional glimpses of\nthe Blue hills.\nChildren\u2019* \u201cKindness Club\u201d\nThe motto of the league is, \u201cKindness\nUplifts the World,\" and the work has\nspread to a number of other cities and\ntowns. The society Is giving as much\nas possible to humane education, but\nIts president says that while humanity\nIs being educated there Is much to be\ndone In relieving the present victims of\nthoughtlessness and cruelty. The Kind\nness club, which was organized some\nyears ago among the boys and girls in\nthe neighborhood of the city home of\nthe league, has been an Influence for\ngood, and a medal is offered each year\nto the child whose record shows the\ngreatest deeds of kindness to animals.\nThe society works in harmony with the\nSociety for the Prevention of Cruelty to\nAnimuls, but in a different field.\nVisitors are welcome at Pine Ridge or\nat the Carver street home, and one who\ncan spend a little time at either of\nthese places cannot fail to be Interested.\nMUSIC STANDS\nWe have \u2019em. Fine nickle\nplate stand for 75c; dandy for\nXmas t.\nT. liams Music House,\n2007 2d Avenue.\nSTOCK MARKET\nHASJVEN TONE\nStreet Is Comparatively Free\nof Pestiferous Manipulation\nPRESIDENT\u2019S MESSAGE\nHa* n Bn\u00abl Effect on Trmllnfp> When\nIt First Appear*\u2014-Lara:e Specu\nlative Account* Arc Taken\nOver\nBy W. G. NICHOLAS\nNew York, December 10.\u2014The market\nhas been comparitively free from pesti\nferous manipulation this week. That is\nbecause the pestiferous manipulators have i\nbeen set back and kept in a state of sub\njection. They were taught that it was\nnot good form to advertise their plays\ntoo openly and that brass band aiid string\ninstruments did not make music pleasant i\nto the public are or alluring to investors.\nIt now\u2019 appears that the much exploit\ned speculative syndicate which had vol\nuntarily come to the assistance of the\nMorgan party was not a real, sure enough\nhard and fast syndicate, but a group of\nsuccessful plungers held together by a\nsort of gentlemen\u2019s agrement, leadership\nin the movement being given to an oper\nator who had been exceptionally success\nful during a series of campaigns extend\ning through three or four years. That\nkind of a record was supposed to have\ntrade him a leader.\nThe experience of the past month has\ndisillusioned this plunger and his friends\nand lias shown them that something be\nsides that is necessary for leadership of\nthe kind that inspires confidence and a\nlarge public following. Thos fact hav\ning been impressed upon the small and\nambitious membership in the gentlemen\u2019s\nsyndicate by bankers of great power, me\ncampaign so noisily began collapsed,\nleaving the street full of mixed emotions\ncf sorrow over losses sustained on ira\nIindent purchases and of joy over the\nsuppression of a bunch of plunging ganib\nblerg when performances had driven\naway the public, cut the commission busi\nness down to nothing and brought the\nStock Exshange into worse repute ^tha.i\nIt was before.\nThe President's message and discussion\nover the prospects of political legisla\ntion have engrossed a large share of the\nattention of Wall street this wee... At\nIhe start-off the (measure had a bad mar\nket effect. It is true that the, main fea\ntures of the document had been com\nmon property In the street for 21 hours\nbefore its submission to Congress, but\nsomething more than a knowledge of\nthe striking passages was required before\nthero could bo a satisfactory analysis.\nSimmered down, the message does not\ngive a whole lot of enjoyment to the\nlarge and anxious element whose prayer\nis to be let alone.\nThe President assures those whom it\nmay concern that no new legislation on\nbusiness subjects need be looked for with\nin a year. That is because yie next Con\ngress will not convene until a year from\nnow. His assurance therefore amount!)\nto little more than a pledge of exemp\nli, n from doing anything for a year that\ncan t be done. Meantime, the existing\nlaws will be \"vigorously enforced\u201d and\ntested out. There Is nothing in this t3\nilli Wall street with exuberant joy.\nThere Is in this section no wild clamor\nfor the enforcement of anti-corporation\nand anti-trust laws, either in whole or\npart. C'ome to think of it, Wall street\ndiscovered that it is not as anxious for\na year\u2019s respite as it is for an early set\ntlement of important pending questions.\n'It is, therefore, heard with satisfaction\nthat there is a possibility of the To\nbacco trust anil Standard Oil cases be\ning argued before the supreme court ear\nly In January instead of the middle of\nFebruary as programmed. There is noth\ning official in tlds announcement, but is\nis generally believed as the report came\nfrom Washington sources usually relia\nble. The street has been taking con\nsiderable Interest In the question of ap\npointments of new Judges on the supreme\nbench and listens eagerly to all the gos\nsip coming from the capital on that\nsubject. So far as can be ascertained,\nthe street has had no candidates though,\nof course, the background log rolling\nwould be kept a deadly secret. The\npublic would be the last to hear anything\nabout it.\nThose who have known ail along how\nthe Interstate commerce commission was\ngoing to decide those freight rate ques\ntions are not quite so cocksure now as\nthey were. The railroads who let it be\nknown that they had presented a case so\nvery strong that it must perforce fa\nvorable influence the commission to de\ncide their way havo apparently seen a\nnew light.\nThey are obliilged to admit tlyit the\nshippers have also made a strong case\nand presented facts and arguments cal\nculated to impress mortal mind, particu\nlarly political mortal mind, with the\nforce of public opinion against showing\nrailroads special favors. It will be a\ngreat and glorious thing for the stock\nmarket when tills rate question will be\ndecided one way or the other. If the\nrailroads should bring all or part of what\nthey arc asking there will be no further\nexcuse for not going ahead with im\nprovements and replacements now held\nin abeyance.\nOn the other hand, if the railroads\nshould be turned down, they can adjust\ntheir affairs to fit conditions and go\nahead on a modified scale. They will\nremember that they have worried along\nand earned dividends without the advance\nin rates and may conclude that they can\npull through without the r'evenue that\nwould be derived from an Increased tax\non traffic. In any event, the situation\nw 111 be cleared of the element of doubt,\nand that will be a big thing from a bus\niness and stock market point of view.\nOne of the incidents of the week has\nbeen the taking over of a large specula\ntive account by interests that did not\ncare to see a big block of stocks thrown\non the market. Late Tuesday afternoon\nand during Wednesday forenoon a line of\nbetween 400,000 and 600,000 shares was\nshifted In open market within the limits\nof one point or less, the principal stocks\nbeing ateel, L'nlon Pacific, Reading and\nAmalgamated Copper.\nThe stuff was tossed out and taken over\nin blocks of 6000 and 10,000 shares and\nIt came so fast as to fairly startle the\nexchange. There Is no certainty as to\nthe identity of the party or parties -who\ntransferred their holdings and got out\nbut the finger points to one or two or\nthree heavyweight operators. And after\nall it doesn't make much difference as\nIt was not a case of threatened insolvency\nbut merely a sudden and violent change\nof heart from rampant and impatient\nbullishness to a position of doubt and\ntimidity.\nMr. Morgan's failure to mutualise the\nEquitable Life Assurance company as\npel half promise made when the great\nbanker took over Mr. Thomas Fortune\nRvan's controlling Interest in that com\npany, caused a mild thrill. No explana\ntions were offered as to why he did not\nannounce a plan at the annual meeting.\nHe simply did not do so, and let it go\nat that.\nRetention of financial control of this\ngreat money collecting agency might\neasily be a matter of the very highest\nImportance should there oome an urgent\nneed for the use of the huge life in\nsurance deposits. Mr. Harrtman always\nfound It very desirable to have control\n~rr~ 1 \"1 R. R. Fares Refunded\nKing's Kash Store\n1923 2nd Avenue\nStupendous Values from the High Class Stock of\nJ. \u2022Matthis Co., New York\nEvery article featured\nin the sale of J. Matthis\nCo.\u2019s stock is absolutely\nfaultless from the view\npoint of fashion, work\nmanship and quality\u2014\neverything high class ex\ncept the price\u2014that is the\nonly thing sliced.\nLadies\u2019 Ready-to-Wear\n$20.00 Taffeta Dresses\n$7.98\nA superb quality taffeta,\nfashioned from the lat\nest Parisian models, in\nblack and desirable\nshades. A $20.00 dress\nfor.$7.98\n$25.00 Suits $14.24\nJaunty short coats, new\nskirts in tweeds, mix\ntures and serges, ex\nquisitely tailored. A\n$25.00 suit.$12.24\n$20.00 Suits $9.97\nYou will find these Suit\nofferings to be the\ngreatest values ever\nshown at this nominal\nprice. The materials\nbeing worth the price.\nA $20.00 suit for $9.97\nTremendous\nReductions on\nT rimmed\nMillinery\nOne-Half Price and Less\nOn Pattern Hats\n$30.00 Hat $14.93\nHferv pattern Hat in\nstock that sold for\n$30.00 has been re\nduced to.$14.93\n$10.00 Ready-to-Wear\nHats $2.33\nIn this section of Street\nHats for immediate\nservice, there have also\nbeen marked reduc\ntions. All $10.00 Hats\nfor .$2.3..\n$5.00 Silk Velvet\nShapes .98c\n$3..W large Velvet\nShapes .76c\n$2.50 French Felt\nShapes .49c\n$2.00 Children\u2019s Soft Felt\nHats .48c\n$5.00 Trimmed\nTurbans .98c\nMens and Boys*\nClothing\nBy buying your Cloth\ning from King you save\nabout one half in price\nand get the acme of qual\nity, style and \\v**hman\nship. \u201cCadet Guaranteed\nClothes,\u201d the creation of\nthe famous clothiers, Aug\nust Bros., ranging in price\nfrom\nS15.00 to $40.00\n$20.00 Suit3 $9.97\nThese Suits are from the\nJ. Mathis Co. stocks\nand are perfectly tail\nored from the season\u2019s\nmost fashionable fab\nricc. A $20.00 suit'\nfor .$9.97\n$30.00 Kuppenheimer\nSuits $10.98\nA limited number of\nthese Suits will be sold\nat this price. Every\none worth $30.00. Your\nchoice Monday .$10.98\n_Bring This for 50c in Cash ___\nOn Purchase of $5.00\nof insurance companies, trust companies\nanti express companies, while conducting\nhis enormous railroad and Industrial cam\npaigns and every other great captain of\nfinance and Industry likes to have as big\na bank roll handy as possible. The\nGoulds,were adepts itt this field for many\nyears, although latterly they have lost\nground there as elsewhere.\n.ludge Gary's latest sunshine interview\non the iron and steel situation fell on\nfriendly ears, contrary to the reception\nusually accorded the canned productions\nof that eminent publicity agent. On tins\noccasion a majority of steel experts were\nIn accord with him In saying that a\nslight improvement can be detected in the\nsteel outlook\u2014not much, to be sure, but\nsome.\nBedrock In that industry seems to have\nbeen struck at least and what change?\nare to be detected are in the way of Im\nprovement. After all the Iron and steel\nbusiness has not been In such a deplora\nble state as many have tried to make It\nuppear. Production has been of moderate\nvolume, but appears smaller than it -Is\nbecause of the large Increase in capacity\narranged for by the great steel com\npanies.\nThis capacity appears extravagant In\nthe light of present conditions and pres\nent consumption, but It will be none too\nlarge with a return of prosperity, and\nthings going at flood tide. The great\ncomplaint, even as recently as four yeatw\nago, was that construction everywhere\nwas kept baey and made costly by In\nability to secure finished steel and Iron.\nThere will be no such congestion on\nthe next big boom. Construction will\nhe accelerated and costly delays will no\nlonger be Incurred by reason thereof.\nNew York banks have been losing\nmoney for a week or more to tlie interior\nand there has been a noticeable hardening\nof interest rates. Time money rates\nshow slight change and the belief still\nprevails in banking circles that after\nthe turn of the year there will be a\nruperabundance of funds In New York\nand other important fiscal centers.\nThe federal court of Philadelphia is\nexpected any day to hand down a decision\nIn the Anthracite coal trust vase. The\ncoal roads are prepared for a finding eith\ner way ,although the supreme court will\nhill have to act before either side will\nfinally accept. A suggestion of coal as\nsets might be a big thing for the stock.\nIndeed, bulls on the Anthrocite stocks\ncould easily he reconciled to a dissolu\ntion of the trust in its present form.\nIlonstlng Ducks\nFrom the National Magazine.\nDucks should be roasted in a quick\noxen and be a little rare than over\ndone, or the meat will be too dry.\nA good filling is made of potatoes,\nmashed and beaten light and seasoned\nwell with saltg&nd pepper, butter, a little\nparsley or sage and two teaspoonfuls\no;' onion juice. This makes ;f delicious\nfilling. I am sure if you will try this\nway of roasting ducks you will be much\npleased.\nAn Unimportant Blunder\nFrom Judge\u2019s Tdbrary.\nProud Artist\u2014\u201cBehold my masterpiece!\nCrass, trees, mountains, sky reflected *.n\nlake!\u201d\nSympathizing Friend\u2014'\u201cVery pretty! But\nwhy do you sign it in the top left-hand\ncorner?\u201d\nProud Artist\u2014\u201cOh, hang It'. The idiots\nhave hung It upside down!\u201d\nW oodpecker and the Duck\nFrom Judge's TJbrary.\nA Woodpecker, looking down from h!\u00bb\nhigh perch on a willow, remarked to a\nDuck, who was preening his \u2022feathers and\nwaddling in and out of the weeds.\n\"I say, what a dull-looking, unattrac\ntive little person you are\u2014and so con\nceited!\u2019\u2019\n\"Not conceited, merely contented,\" re\nplied the Duck.\n\"TIow can that be,\u201d alked the Wood\npecker. \"when you Imvc neither size nor\nplumage to commend you? Now, look\nover there at those handsome ducks with\nthe green bodies and red beads\u2014those\nare what T cal) beautiful birds!\u201d\n\"That, proves,\" replied the Duck, \"that\nthe only brilliant thing about you is your\ntopknot, and that\u2019s on the outside. If\nyou didn\u2019t spend most of your days with\nyour head in a hole and the rest of your\ntime in knocking, you might have ac\nquired sufficient discernment to know\nthat those Ducks, which you so greatly\nadmire are Decoys\u2014mere wooden things\npainted red and green and staked out\nthere to catch Suckers like you.\"\nMORAL.\nThere\u2019s m&ny a clothier's dummy wear\ning a dress suit and a 44 chest.\nIIto Sl)\u00abM(|0|U\nIt\u2019s a long road that has no tacks.\nA taclc avoided Is a tire repaired.\nThe race is to the swift, provided thp\nconstable doesn\u2019t telephone ahead.\nOn an auto honeymoon, love mgkes\nthe world go round\u2014but the engine de\nmands gasoline.\nA honk in time may prevent a fine.\nThe loudest horn doesn\u2019t always be\nlong to the biggest car.\nMotorists swear by their cars; pedes\ntrians them.\nIt's a rare car that doesn't earn\u201d mor%\nthan one crank.\nR\u00bbd Cross Seals on Sale Here\u2014Help the Anti-Tuberculosis Campaign.\nExclusive Offerings for\nEarly Christmas Buyers\ni\u2014nr 1 f\\\nLadies\u2019 Hand Bags\nLadies\u2019 Purses\nGentlemen\u2019s Poeketbooka\nLeather Wallets\nLoose Leaf Memorandum\nand Price Books\n1911 Diaries\nDate Books\nGift Bibles, leather bound\nGift Books of Sentiment\nNew and elegant things\nin Writing Stationery\nin Gift Boxes\n1\nLargest assortment, g|^\nboth Plain and |p\nGold Mounted SP\nHandsome Albums\nCard Cases\nPicture Calendars\nCalendar Pads for the Desk\n9\nCalendar Pads, all sizes\nfor making Xmas Gifts\nFancy Desk Pads\nHoliday Stickers\nFriendship Blotters\nPanel Pictures\nEngraved and Embossed Goods and Illuminated\nChristmas Cards\n\nEngraved \u201cChristmas Finest Engraved Visiting Kenre Cards\nGreetings\u201d and Business Curds Dance Cards\nCards to Order Steel Die Monogram and Fancy Tasseled Pencils\nEngraved Book Labels Embossed Writing aii Colors\nHand Illuminated Stationery\nChristmas Cards We operate our own complete Engraving and Embossing\nPictorial Christmas Cards Plant, and all work is executed in the most elegant manner,\nArt Calendars on Crane\u2019s and Hurd\u2019s finest st